Dear Wystan,
 
Nothing changed because no one did what I asked. Seriously, I agree with
Ira, Gary and Andrew--to say that poets can't/don't have power is
ridiculous. As Ira preceptively points out, the problem of poets' power
is greater in the avant garde world because that world is smaller and
sort of isolated.
 
In a situation where poets are, for the most part, their own audience,
critics and publishers, having some stature, clout or influence can be a
pretty big deal. Most poets behave as if they're only too aware of this,
whether they admit it or not.
 
On Wed, 5 Apr 1995, Wystan Curnow wrote:
 
> Dear Selby,
>            Nothing changed.
>                           Wystan
