Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Andrew Joron <ajoron@EMF.NET>
Subject:      poetry & neo-chamber music
 
Poetry & jazz has become almost a "canonical" synthesis, still a potent
one of course (witness Lacy, etc.).  Is there a tradition of contemporary
poems set to music other than jazz?  I've come across a single speciman,
on Crammed Discs, a Belgian label specializing in new music/ambient/neo-
chamber music: _When God Was Famous_, a 1989 release with texts by Paul
Celan, Apollinaire, Gottfried Benn, Paul Eluard, Delmore Schwartz, and
Bob Kaufman, and music by Samy Birnbaum & Benjamin Lew. I'd be interested
to learn of other recordings of extra-jazz poetry.
                                  Andrew Joron
